The paper deals with deep convolutional networks for semantic image segmentation, which is a computer vision task, and proposes a method for self-supervised pre-training of the network. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition). The paper also introduces a new tuning stage that improves the performance of the self-supervised method, which involves machine learning techniques such as fine-tuning and discriminative loss, making cs.LG (Machine Learning) another likely sub-category. The paper also discusses the design of a proxy task, which involves unsupervised learning, making cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) a possible sub-category. The paper also mentions the use of limited pixel-wise annotations, which involves natural language processing techniques such as text classification, making cs.CL (Computation and Language) another possible sub-category. Finally, the paper deals with mixing and matching patches from the target set, which involves multimedia techniques such as image processing and computer graphics, making cs.MM (Multimedia) a possible sub-category as well.
